	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=117530><span id=Guru>Calabar</span></a><br><b><span id=Guru>Guru</span></b><br><span id=notbold>210 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [5.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>I’m in complete agreement with your post.&nbsp;&nbsp;I’ve been lucky enough to spend most of my time in Norrath as a member of an excellent guild.  The Moonshadows are a small, well-respected group of friends and I learned most of my EQ etiquette by grouping with guild members.  When your soloing you can afford to be selfish.  All the loot and all the responsibility is yours.  As long as you aren’t kill stealing or training those around you, nobody really cares what you do.  But grouping is different.  You are all working together to achieve a common goal.  As such you have to learn to play nicely together.  If you aren’t willing to think of others as well as yourself you have no business being in a group.  <br><br>Unfortunately, the world of Norrath, just as the real world, has is share of spoiled, selfish twits who do things only to please themselves even at the cost of those around them.  The only advice I can give is to keep in mind that these spoiled brats are in the minority.  There are a lot of really nice people out there who are fun to meat and group with.  Try not to let the few bad apples spoil your game.  In a way grouping with the spoiled brats every now and then is a good thing.  They give us a basis for comparison.  So the next time we have a good group we can really appreciate it. </p>&nbsp;<br><b>Pait Spiritwalker</b><br>Vah Shir Shaman, 61st Season<br><b>Jondor</b><br>Barbarian Beastlord, 54th Season<br><br><b>Seventh Hammer</b> </td></td></tr>
